Bidirectional Encoder Representations from Transformers (BERT) is a groundbreaking large language model introduced by Google researchers in 2018. Utilizing the transformer encoder architecture, BERT revolutionized the field of Natural Language Processing (NLP) by providing contextualized representations of words, greatly surpassing the performance of previous models. Trained using masked token prediction and next sentence prediction, BERT was one of the first models to truly capture the nuanced meaning of words in context. While bigger and stronger models exist today BERT is still an engineering marvel that can perform very well on a variety of tasks.

In this article, we will explore how to use BERT for sentiment analysis, a common NLP task that involves determining the sentiment expressed in text. We will begin by understanding the underlying principles of BERT, followed by implementing a sentiment analysis model using pre-trained BERT weights that we will then fine-tune. We will then perform a variety on experiments on the model to better understand it's workings and the performance/compute tradeoff relevant to LLM's.

For complete code, refer to: https://colab.research.google.com/drive/1taVSgrCoY5DxwurXm7E46W2HVv0wFm4U?usp=sharing

## The Model

The BERT model has 2 main parts, the embedding layer and the encoder layer, as shown in the diagram below. Do note that the diagram is a simplification, there are additional operations performed such as normalization at various points, see the original BERT paper \href{here} for a complete overview of the model.

<br>

<div align="center">
<img src="data:image/png;base64," alt="" />
</div>
<br>

The embedding layer in BERT converts input text into dense, real-valued vectors for processing by the encoder. It combines token embeddings to represent the meaning of each word or sub-word, segment embeddings to differentiate between sentences, and position embeddings to capture the order of tokens. These embeddings are summed and passed to the encoder layer.

Each encoder block consists of a multi-headed attention layer followed by a feed-forward layer. I will briefly describe the attention mechanism. Essentially, attention allows the model to dinamically decide (based on the input), which weights to use and to what degree. It works as follows, given an input query vector $q$,
$$
\text{Attention}(q, (k_{1:m}, v_{1:m})) = \sum_{i=1}^m \alpha_i(q, k_{1:m})v_i \in \mathbb{R}^v
$$
$$
\text{Where} \ \ \ \alpha_i(q, k_{1:m}) = \text{softmax}_i([a(q, k_1), ..., a(q, k_m)])
$$
<br>
$a(q, k)$ is the attention score function, which gives a similarity rating between $q$ and $k$. A simple choice for $a$ is $q$ and $k$ are of the same size $d$ is:

$$
a(q, k) = \frac{q^{\intercal} k}{\sqrt{d}}
$$
For differently sized queries and keys, we can map them to a common embedding space and then pass them trhough a neural network. We can simplify this whole process and write in matrix form for a minibatch of size $n$ as follows:

$$
\text{Attention}(Q, K, V) = \text{softmax}\bigg(\frac{Q K^{\intercal}}{\sqrt{d}}\bigg)V \in \mathbb{R}^{n \times v}
$$

Self attention, is when the query, keys, and values, are derived from the input, this can be understood as the model processing which parts of the input are relevant relative to other parts of the input.

In multi-headed attention, many different attention matrices are used to capture different notions of similiarity. They are all then projected to a common space using projection matrices.

<br>

## Implementation

While thankfully, we don't have to write and train the BERT model, we do have to define the training loop. The code below defines the training loop and defines a callback that will register loss values at different points in training.

```python
#Track loss for plotting
class LossTrackingCallback(TrainerCallback):

    def __init__(self):
        self.losses = []

    def on_train_end(self, args, state, control, **kwargs):
        for log in state.log_history:
          if 'loss' in log:
            self.losses.append(log['loss'])



def train_bert(model, train_data, lr=2e-5, epochs=5, batch_size=64, weight_decay=0.01, verbose = True):

    if not verbose:
      logging_strategy = "no"
      evaluation_strategy = "no"
    else:
      logging_strategy = "step"
      evaluation_strategy = "epoch"


    # Training arguments
    training_args = TrainingArguments(
        output_dir="results",
        num_train_epochs=epochs,
        learning_rate=lr,
        per_device_train_batch_size=batch_size,
        per_device_eval_batch_size=batch_size,
        metric_for_best_model="accuracy",
        weight_decay=weight_decay,
        evaluation_strategy=evaluation_strategy,
        disable_tqdm=not verbose,
        logging_strategy=logging_strategy,
        logging_steps=10,
        report_to="none",
    )

    # Initialize the custom callback
    loss_tracking_callback = LossTrackingCallback()

    # Initialize the Trainer
    trainer = Trainer(
        model=model,
        args=training_args,
        train_dataset=train_data,
        eval_dataset=test_data_bert,
        compute_metrics=compute_metrics,
        callbacks=[loss_tracking_callback]
    )

    # Train the model
    if verbose:
      t0 = time.time()
      trainer.train()
      tf = time.time()
      delta_t = round(tf - t0, 2)
      print(f'Training time: {delta_t} seconds for {epochs} epochs of training\n')

    else:
      with suppress_stdout():
        trainer.train()

    # Return the losses for the last epoch
    return loss_tracking_callback.losses
```

Now we can easily import the pretrained bert model as follows.

```python
model = BertForSequenceClassification.from_pretrained('bert-base-uncased', num_labels=6)
```

## Dataset

Before proceeding to testing and experimentation, we take a moment to understand the task. We will by using BERT for sentimment analysis. The Emotion dataset consists of English Twitter messages annotated with six basic emotions: anger, fear, joy, love, sadness,
and surprise. The dataset provides two configurations: "split"
and "unsplit." In the "split" configuration, there are a total of
20,000 examples split into training, validation, and test sets.
The "unsplit" configuration contains a larger dataset with a to-
tal of 416,809 examples in a single training split. We will be using the split configuration for our purposes. 

Each example
in the dataset is associated with two main data fields: "text,"
which represents the Twitter message as a string feature, and
"label," a classification label indicating one of the six emotions
with corresponding numerical values (0 for sadness, 1 for joy,
2 for love, 3 for anger, 4 for fear, and 5 for surprise). We do not perform any additional pre-processing of the text as that is all handled by the BERT tokenizer. The data is loaded using the below code.

```python
# Load the dataset
dataset = load_dataset('dair-ai/emotion')
train_data, test_data = dataset['train'], dataset['test']

# Extract labels from train and test data
train_labels = train_data['label']
test_labels = test_data['label']
```

<br>

## Training and Experimentation

Now we will fine-tune the model for our specific requirments in a variety of ways, trying to find the best compromise between efficiency and performance. This will invlove hyper-parameter tuning but also training different parts of the model with varying amounts of data and regularization. Do note that training was conducted on a A100 cloud GPU through Google Colab, training times reflect this.

### Depth of Training

As previously explained, after the embedding layer, the model consists of 12 encoder blocks plus a classification layer. We will see how depth of fine-tuning affects performance and training speed. First, we will only train the classification layer, we will then try training the last 2 encoder blocks, the last 6, and then the entire model.

Below is the code which trains the classification layer only and the last two encoder blocks only. To see the the entirety of the code refer to the introduction.

```python
# Only train classifier layer

model = BertForSequenceClassification.from_pretrained('bert-base-uncased', num_labels=6)
model.to(device)

#Freeze all BERT blocks
for param in model.base_model.parameters():
    param.requires_grad = False

print('Only Fine-Tuning Classifier Layer:')
loss = train_bert(model, train_data_bert)


#Only train last 2 blocks + classifier layer

model = BertForSequenceClassification.from_pretrained('bert-base-uncased', num_labels=6)
model.to(device)

#Freeze all BERT blocks
for param in model.base_model.parameters():
    param.requires_grad = False

#Unfreeze last 2 blocks
for param in model.bert.encoder.layer[-2:].parameters():
    param.requires_grad = True

print('Only Fine-Tuning Last 2 Blocks:')
loss = train_bert(model, train_data_bert)
```
We find the following test accuracies and training times after 5 epochs of training:

```
    Depth             Accuracy    Time
-------------------   --------    -----
  Classifier only       0.37       126s
  2 Blocks              0.83       156s
  6 Blocks              0.90       219s
  12 Blocks             0.93       323s
```

As one would expect, increasing depth of fine-tuning increases accuracy, however, we do see diminishing returns, with only a 3% increase in accuracy and a 47% increase in training time when going from a depth of 6 encoder blocks to 12 encoder blocks. We do therefore proceed with training at a depth of 6 blocks for subsequent experiments and tests.

### Attention VS. Linear Layers

It is interesting to see which components of the model benefit more from fine-tuning, we will try only training the attention components of each encoder block and only the linear components to see the difference in performence and efficiency. This is accomplished by the code below.

```python
#Only train attention components of last 6 blocks + classifier layer
model = BertForSequenceClassification.from_pretrained('bert-base-uncased', num_labels=6)
model.to(device)

#Freeze all BERT blocks
for param in model.base_model.parameters():
    param.requires_grad = False

#Unfreeze attention layers of last 6 blocks
for i in range(1, 7):
  for param in model.bert.encoder.layer[-i].attention.parameters():
    param.requires_grad = True

print('Only Fine-Tuning Attention Layers:')
loss = train_bert(model, train_data_bert)

model = BertForSequenceClassification.from_pretrained('bert-base-uncased', num_labels=6)
model.to(device)

#Freeze all BERT blocks
for param in model.base_model.parameters():
    param.requires_grad = False

#Unfreeze linear layers of last 6 blocks
for i in range(1, 7):
  for param in model.bert.encoder.layer[-i].intermediate.parameters():
    param.requires_grad = True

print('Only Fine-Tuning Linear Layers:')
loss = train_bert(model, train_data_bert)
```
We find the following results after 5 epochs of training:
```
    Layers    Accuracy    Time
  ---------   --------    -----
  Attention     0.85       190s
  Linear        0.80       182s
```
It does seem that Attention layers have a slightly bigger impact on everall model performance compared to the linear layers, this is expected because there is simply a larger number of parameters in the Attention layers. No significant difference in training time however.

<br>

### Learning Rate Tuning

We train the model for 3 epochs at 4 different learning rate to see which results in the fastest convergence. This is accomplished by the code below.

```python
#Learning rate
fig = plt.subplot()
learning_rates = [2e-3, 2e-4, 2e-5, 2e-6]

for alpha in learning_rates:

  model = BertForSequenceClassification.from_pretrained('bert-base-uncased', num_labels=6)
  model.to(device)

  #Freeze all BERT blocks
  for param in model.base_model.parameters():
    param.requires_grad = False

  #Unfreeze last 6 blocks
  for param in model.bert.encoder.layer[-6:].parameters():
    param.requires_grad = True

  print(f'Learning rate: {alpha}')
  loss = train_bert(model, train_data_bert, lr = alpha, epochs = 3)
  plt.plot(range(len(loss)), loss, label = f'Learning Rate: {alpha}')

#Plot (Last Epoch Training)
plt.legend()
fig.spines[['right', 'top']].set_visible(False)
fig.legend(frameon = False)
plt.xlabel('Iteration/10')
plt.ylabel('Loss')
```
We get the following accuracies after 3 epochs of training.

```
    Learning Rate     Accuracy
  -----------------  ----------
        2e-3            0.35
        2e-4            0.93
        2e-5            0.89
        2e-6            0.55
```
We proceed with a learning rate of 0.0002, which results in the fastest convergence of the tested rates, as further evidenced by the graph below.

### Weight Decay


L2-regularization is a widely used regularization technique that helps prevent overfitting. We investiage it's effect on the fine-tuning process. We train the model for 3 epochs at 4 different regularization strengths, 1, 0.1, 0.01, and 0.001. This is achieved by the code below.

```python
#L2 Regularization Strength

#Learning rate
fig = plt.subplot()
weight_decays = [1, 0.1, 0.01, 0.001]

for lambdaa in weight_decays:

  model = BertForSequenceClassification.from_pretrained('bert-base-uncased', num_labels=6)
  model.to(device)

  #Freeze all BERT blocks
  for param in model.base_model.parameters():
    param.requires_grad = False

  #Unfreeze last 6 blocks
  for param in model.bert.encoder.layer[-6:].parameters():
    param.requires_grad = True

  print(f'Weight Decay: {lambdaa}')
  loss = train_bert(model, train_data_bert, lr = 2e-4, weight_decay = lambdaa, epochs = 3)
  plt.plot(loss, label = f'L2 Reg. Strength: {lambdaa}')
```
With the following results:

```
    Reg. Strength     Accuracy
  -----------------  ----------
       1.000            0.93
       0.100            0.92
       0.010            0.93
       0.001            0.92
```
We find no difference in applying L2-regularization to the fine-tuning process, this is somewhat expected since this last bit of training we are doing is very small compared to the pre-training performed on BERT, so regularizing this last little bit is unsurprizingly irrelevant.

### Amount of Data Needed for Training

It is interesting to study the performence/efficiency tradeoff in the context of the number of examples used in training, up to this point we have been using 16,000 instances in training, we will try training with 8000 and 4000 examples. This is achieved by the code below.

```python
def valid_sample(sample, min_per_label):
    label_counts = Counter([example['label'] for example in sample])
    return all(count >= min_per_label for count in label_counts.values())


def get_valid_sample(dataset, sample_size, min_per_label):
    dataset_list = [dataset[i] for i in range(len(dataset))]
    while True:
        sample = random.sample(dataset_list, sample_size)
        if valid_sample(sample, min_per_label):
            return sample

# Keep Validation Set same size
# Investigate effect of training data size on performance

dataset_sizes = [16000, 8000, 4000]

for size in dataset_sizes:

    print(f'Training on {size} documents:')
    data_sample = get_valid_sample(train_data_bert, size, 1)

    model = BertForSequenceClassification.from_pretrained('bert-base-uncased', num_labels=6)
    model.to(device)

    # Freeze all BERT blocks
    for param in model.base_model.parameters():
        param.requires_grad = False

    # Unfreeze last 6 blocks
    for param in model.bert.encoder.layer[-6:].parameters():
        param.requires_grad = True

    loss = train_bert(model, data_sample, lr = 2e-4)
```
With the following results.
```
    Num. Documents      Accuracy        Time
  -----------------    ----------     ---------
        8000            0.92             115s
        4000            0.90              64s
```
We see a 44% decrease in training time at the cost of 2% accuracy when going from 8000 to 4000 training documents. Depending on ones specific performance/efficiency requirements, adjusting the training size correspondingly seems like a promising avenue.

### Shrinking the Model

Another way we could potentially sacrifice performance for efficiency is by completely removing certain parts of the model, speficially, we remove encoder blocks. We will evaluate the model when it only has it's last 6, and last 2 blocks. This is achieved by the code below.

```python
# What if we only use the last 6 encoder blocks (For Training and Evaluation)

model = BertForSequenceClassification.from_pretrained('bert-base-uncased', num_labels=6)

# Remove the first six encoder layers
model.bert.encoder.layer = model.bert.encoder.layer[6:]
print('Peformance of BERT if we only use the last 6 encoder blocks:')
loss = train_bert(model, train_data_bert)


model = BertForSequenceClassification.from_pretrained('bert-base-uncased', num_labels=6)

# Remove the first ten encoder blocks
model.bert.encoder.layer = model.bert.encoder.layer[-2:]
print('Peformance of BERT if we only use the last 2 encoder blocks:')
loss = train_bert(model, train_data_bert)
```
With the following results.

```
    Num. Blocks      Accuracy        Time
  --------------    ----------     ---------
        6              0.92           171s
        2              0.92            67s
```
We see essentially no decrease in model performance when going from 6 to 2 encoder blocks, but we do see a significant decrease in training time.

## Final Models and Conclusion

We performed a variety of experiments to study the performance/efficiency tradeoffs of a large language model like BERT. The code below trains and evaluates 3 versions of BERT, one which we did not fine-tune at all, straight out the box, another maximized for performance (where the entire model is trained on the entire dataset for 5 epochs), and yet another which strikes the best compromise between efficiency and performance based on our experiments (trained on a quarter of the dataset, with only 2 encoder blocks). This is achieved by the code below.

```python 
test_loader = DataLoader(test_data_bert, batch_size=32)

model_accuracies = []
model_training_times = []


# Base BERT
model = BertForSequenceClassification.from_pretrained('bert-base-uncased', num_labels=6)
base_bert_accuracy = evaluate_model(model, test_loader)
base_bert_training_time = 0

model_accuracies.append(base_bert_accuracy)
model_training_times.append(base_bert_training_time)

# Tuned BERT (Power)
start_time = time.time()
train_bert(model, train_data_bert, test_data_bert, epochs = 5, lr = 2e-4, verbose = False)
tuned_bert_power_training_time = time.time() - start_time

tuned_bert_power_accuracy = evaluate_model(model, test_loader)

model_accuracies.append(tuned_bert_power_accuracy)
model_training_times.append(tuned_bert_power_training_time)

# Tuned BERT (Efficiency)
model = BertForSequenceClassification.from_pretrained('bert-base-uncased', num_labels=6)
model.bert.encoder.layer = model.bert.encoder.layer[-2:] # Remove first 10 encoder blocks
train_sample = get_valid_sample(train_data_bert, 4000, 1) # Use 4000 training documents
start_time = time.time()
train_bert(model, train_sample, test_data_bert, epochs = 5, lr = 2e-4, verbose = False)
end_time = time.time()
tuned_bert_efficiency_training_time = end_time - start_time

tuned_bert_efficiency_accuracy = evaluate_model(model, test_loader)

model_accuracies.append(tuned_bert_efficiency_accuracy)
model_training_times.append(tuned_bert_efficiency_training_time)


table = PrettyTable()
table.field_names = ["Model Type", "Accuracy (%)", "Training Time (s)"]

# Adding rows to the table
model_types = ["Naive Bayes", "Base BERT", "Tuned BERT (Power)", "Tuned BERT (Efficiency)"]
for i in range(len(model_types)):
    table.add_row([model_types[i], f"{model_accuracies[i]:.2f}", f"{model_training_times[i]:.2f}"])

print(table)
```
Which produces the following table.

```
+-------------------------+--------------+-------------------+
|        Model Type       | Accuracy (%) | Training Time (s) |
+-------------------------+--------------+-------------------+
|        Base BERT        |    28.12     |        0.00       |
|    Tuned BERT (Power)   |    96.88     |       324.19      |
| Tuned BERT (Efficiency) |    93.75     |       14.77       |
+-------------------------+--------------+-------------------+
```
By considering efficiency, we managed decrease training time by 95% while only sacrificing 3.13% of accuracy. This is quite remarkable, and shows the importance of adapting these large models to the specific requirements of a particular task. More generally, we have learned that a large language model, even a somewhat outdated one, is very performant on this sentiment analysis task, it even seems to be too large for the purposes of simple sentiment analysis and as such can be shrunk and cut down with very little effect on performance.
